{"id": "duc04-testb-18:9#29", "contents": "Speculation is rife in the capital about the next steps in the conflict. Some believe that the recent poll showing increased support for resignation as a way to avoid a trial may weaken President Clinton's resolve. Others think that the Republicans, facing dismal poll numbers, may be the first to back down. However, with a majority in the Senate, the Republicans have the power to end a trial at any time after January 6. Meanwhile, Representative J.C. Watts of Oklahoma emphasized that polls should not dictate the decision, saying that what is popular is not always right, and that the line between right and wrong should be drawn with principle, not public opinion."}
